Definition 2.30. We call admissible automorphism of $\mathbb{K}^{{\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})}$ the algebra automorphisms induced by elements of $\tau\in\mathfrak{B}_{n}$, via $\Psi(E_{A})=E_{\tau(A)}$. In particular, (1) $\Psi$ is of $\sigma$-permutation type if $\tau=\sigma$ belongs to the subgroup $\mathfrak{S}_{n}$ of $\mathfrak{B}_{n}$ (in particular, we say $\Psi$ is a flip if $\tau$ is a transposition), (2) $\Psi$ is of $B$-inversion type if $\tau(A)=B\Delta A$ belongs to the subgroup $({\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n},\Delta))$ of $\mathfrak{B}^{n}$. In particular, we say that $\Psi$ is an elementary inversion if $B$ is a singleton, $B=\{i\}$, and $\Psi$ is the central inversion, if $B=\mathsf{n}$. We use the same terminology for the corresponding pairs of anchor-compatible morphisms, having the corresponding type as base-map $\Psi$.
Definition 2.1 (Normalization: source, target, anchor). When $V=W=\mathbb{K}$, the anchor is a map $\Upsilon:\mathbb{K}^{2}\times\mathbb{K}^{2}\to\mathbb{K}^{2}\times\mathbb{K}^{2}$, and when $(t,s)\in\mathbb{K}^{2}$ is fixed, then we have a (linear) map $\Upsilon_{(t,s)}:\mathbb{K}^{2}\to\mathbb{K}^{2}$. The standard basis in the domain of $\Upsilon_{(t,s)}$ will be denoted by $e_{\emptyset}:=(1,0)$, $e_{1}:=(0,1)$, and the standard basis in its range by $E_{\emptyset}:=(1,0)$ and $E_{1}:=(0,1)$, so $\mathbf{v}=v_{\emptyset}e_{\emptyset}+v_{1}e_{1}$. We make the choice to associate $E_{\emptyset}$ with “source” and $E_{1}$ with “target”, that is, we let $\displaystyle\alpha(\mathbf{v})=\alpha(v_{0}e_{\emptyset}+v_{1}e_{1})$ $\displaystyle=(v_{0}+sv_{1})E_{\emptyset},$ $\displaystyle\beta(\mathbf{v})=\beta(v_{0}e_{\emptyset}+v_{1}e_{1})$ $\displaystyle=(v_{0}+tv_{1})E_{1},$ $\displaystyle\Upsilon(\mathbf{v})=\Upsilon(v_{0}e_{\emptyset}+v_{1}e_{1})$ $\displaystyle=(v_{0}+sv_{1})E_{\emptyset}+(v_{0}+tv_{1})E_{1}.$ In other terms, $\Upsilon(e_{\emptyset})=E_{\emptyset}+E_{1},\qquad\Upsilon(e_{1})=sE_{% \emptyset}+tE_{1}.$ With respect to ordered bases, with “usual” ordering $(e_{\emptyset},e_{1})$, $(E_{\emptyset},E_{1})$, these linear maps correspond to the matrices $\alpha=\begin{pmatrix}1&s\end{pmatrix},\qquad\beta=\begin{pmatrix}1&t\end{% pmatrix},\qquad\Upsilon_{(t,s)}=\begin{pmatrix}1&s\\ 1&t\end{pmatrix}.$ As usual, dual bases are denoted by $((e_{\emptyset})^{*},(e_{1})^{*})$, resp., $((E_{\emptyset})^{*},(E_{1})^{*})$. Thus $\displaystyle\alpha$ $\displaystyle=e_{\emptyset}^{*}+s\cdot e_{1}^{*},$ $\displaystyle\beta$ $\displaystyle=e_{\emptyset}^{*}+t\cdot e_{1}^{*},$ $\displaystyle\Upsilon_{(t,s)}$ $\displaystyle=\alpha\otimes E_{\emptyset}+\beta\otimes E_{1}=e_{\emptyset}^{*}% \otimes E_{\emptyset}+e_{1}^{*}\otimes E_{1}+s\,e_{1}^{*}\otimes E_{\emptyset}% +t\,e_{\emptyset}^{*}\otimes E_{1}.$
Definition C.4. By definition, the $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$-law $\underline{V}$ of a $\mathbb{K}$-module $V$ shall be given by algebraic scalar extension (as in Example C.1), and likewise for the mapping law corresponding to a $\mathbb{K}$-linear map. In other words, the category of $\mathbb{K}$-linear spaces shall be imbedded into the functor category $\mathbf{Fn}(\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}},\mathbf{Sets}^{\mathbf{2}})$ in the natural way.
Definition 2.16. For any $\mathbb{K}$-module $V$, the canonical isomorphism $V\oplus V=(V\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}\mathbb{K})\oplus(V\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}\mathbb% {K})=V\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}\mathbb{K}^{2}$ gives an identification $V^{\{1\}}_{(t,s)}=V\times V=V\otimes_{\mathbb{K}}\mathbb{K}_{(t,s)}^{\{1\}}$. By restricted iteration, let $\mathbb{K}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}^{\mathsf{n}}=\mathbb{K}_{(t_{1},s_{1})}^{% \{1\}}\otimes\ldots\otimes\mathbb{K}_{(t_{n},s_{n})}^{\{n\}}.$ The canonical basis $e_{\emptyset},e_{k}$ in each factor $\mathbb{K}_{(t_{k},s_{k})}^{\{k\}}$ gives rise to a canonical basis in the $\mathbb{K}$-module $\mathbb{K}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}^{\mathsf{n}}$, indexed by elements $A\in{\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})$, and given by $e_{A}=\otimes_{k=1}^{n}e_{{\{k\}}\cap A}.$
Definition 3.2. The functor category $\mathbf{Fn}(\mathbf{talg}_{\mathbb{K},n},\mathbf{Sets}^{\mathbf{2}})$ is called the category of $(\mathbb{K},n)$-space laws: its objects are called $(\mathbb{K},n)$-space laws $\underline{M}$, and its morphisms $\underline{f}$ are called $(\mathbb{K},n)$-mapping laws. A $(\mathbb{K},\infty)$-space law (or just: $\mathbb{K}$-space law) is a functor in $\mathbf{Fn}(\mathbf{talg}_{\mathbb{K}},\mathbf{Sets}^{\mathsf{2}})$, and a $(\mathbb{K},\infty)$-mapping law is a morphism in this category. We demand explicitly that the category of locally linear sets together with their (restrictions) of linear maps be considered as subcategory of this functor category in the way given by the following Example 3.1.
Definition 1.11. We denote by $\mathbf{Llin}_{\mathbb{K},n}$ the category whose objects are pairs $(U,V)$, where $V$ is a topological $\mathbb{K}$-module and $U\subset V$ a non-empty open subset, and morphisms are $C_{\mathbb{K},n}$-maps $f:U\to U^{\prime}$. (For $n=0$, morphisms are continuous maps, and for $n=\infty$, these are maps that are $C_{\mathbb{K},n}$ for all $n\in\mathbb{N}$.)
Definition 2.28. Let $\phi_{i}:\mathbb{K}\to\mathbb{K}$ affine maps, $i=1,\ldots,n$, and $\phi=\phi_{1}\times\ldots\times\phi_{n}:\mathbb{K}^{n}\to\mathbb{K}^{n}$. Then $\phi$ induces an anchor-preserving morphism, called of affine type, $\phi^{*}:\mathbb{K}_{(\mathbf{t}^{\prime},\mathbf{s}^{\prime})}^{\mathsf{n}}% \to\mathbb{K}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}^{\mathsf{n}}$. In particular, we say that $\phi^{*}$ is (1) of translation type if $\phi^{*}$ is the tensor product of morphisms of translation type, parametrized by $\mu=(\mu_{1},\ldots,\mu_{n})\in\mathbb{K}^{n}$, $t_{i}^{\prime}=t_{i}+\mu$, $s_{i}^{\prime}=s_{i}+\mu$, (2) of scaling type if $\phi^{*}$ is the tensor product of morphisms of scaling type, parametrized by $\lambda=(\lambda_{1},\ldots,\lambda_{n})\in\mathbb{K}^{n}$, $t_{i}^{\prime}=\lambda_{i}t_{t},s_{i}^{\prime}=\lambda_{i}s_{i}$.
Definition C.2. Let $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$ be some (small) subcategory of $\mathbf{Alg}_{\mathbb{K}}^{\mathbf{2}}$ (containing at least the trivial anchor as object, and the unique morphism of the trivial anchor to any other object as morphism). A $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$-space law is a functor $\underline{M}:\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}\to\mathbf{Sets}^{\mathbf{2}},\quad$ from $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$ to the category $\mathbf{Sets}^{\mathbf{2}}$ of anchored sets: for very object $\Upsilon:\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{A}^{\prime}$ of $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$, we have sets $M_{\mathbb{A}}$ and $M_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}$ and a set-map $M_{\Upsilon}:M_{\mathbb{A}}\to M_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}$, and for every $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$-morphism $(\phi:\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{B},\phi^{\prime}:\mathbb{A}^{\prime}\to\mathbb{B}^{% \prime})$, we have a pair of maps $(M_{\phi}:M_{\mathbb{A}}\to M_{\mathbb{B}},M_{\phi^{\prime}}:M_{\mathbb{A}^{% \prime}}\to M_{\mathbb{B}^{\prime}})$ commuting with anchors and satisfying the functorial rules $M_{\mathrm{id}}=\mathrm{id}_{M_{\mathbb{A}}}$ and $M_{\phi\circ\psi}=M_{\phi}\circ M_{\psi}$, $M_{\phi^{\prime}\circ\psi^{\prime}}=M_{\phi^{\prime}}\circ M_{\psi^{\prime}}$. The trivial anchor $\mathrm{id}_{\mathbb{K}}$ shall give rise to the “trivial anchored set” $\mathrm{id}:M_{\mathbb{K}}\to M_{\mathbb{K}}$, called the underlying set of $\underline{M}$. A morphism between $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$-space laws $\underline{M}$ and $\underline{N}$, also called $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$-mapping law, is a natural transformation $\underline{f}:\underline{M}\to\underline{N}$, i.e., for each object $\Upsilon:\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{A}^{\prime}$ of $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$, there is an anchor-compatible pair $f_{\mathbb{A}}:M_{\mathbb{A}}\to N_{\mathbb{A}},\qquad f_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}% :M_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}\to N_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}$ varying functorially with $\Upsilon$: for any $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$-morphism $(\phi:\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{B},\phi^{\prime}:\mathbb{A}^{\prime}\to\mathbb{B}^{% \prime})$ and space laws $\underline{M},\underline{N}$, there are maps $M_{\phi}$, $N_{\phi}$ such that $N_{\phi}\circ f_{\mathbb{A}}=f_{\mathbb{B}}\circ M_{\phi}$ and $N_{\phi^{\prime}}\circ f_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}=f_{\mathbb{B}^{\prime}}\circ M_% {\phi^{\prime}}$ $\begin{matrix}M_{\mathbb{A}}&\buildrel f_{\mathbb{A}}\over{\longrightarrow}&N_% {\mathbb{A}}\cr M_{\phi}\downarrow&&\phantom{M_{f}}\downarrow N_{\phi},\cr M_{% \mathbb{B}}&\buildrel f_{\mathbb{B}}\over{\longrightarrow}&N_{\mathbb{B}}\end{% matrix}\qquad\quad\begin{matrix}M_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}&\buildrel f_{\mathbb{A% }^{\prime}}\over{\longrightarrow}&N_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}\cr M_{\phi^{\prime}}% \downarrow&&\phantom{M_{f}}\downarrow N_{\phi^{\prime}}.\cr M_{\mathbb{B}^{% \prime}}&\buildrel f_{\mathbb{B}^{\prime}}\over{\longrightarrow}&N_{\mathbb{B}% ^{\prime}}\end{matrix}$ The map $f_{\mathbb{K}}:M_{\mathbb{K}}\to N_{\mathbb{K}}$ is called the underlying set-map of $\underline{f}$. The functor category of $\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$-space laws and their morphisms, denoted by $\mathbf{Fn}(\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}},\mathbf{Sets}^{\mathbf{2}})$ is the (large) category whose objects are functors $\underline{M}$ and morphisms natural transformations $\underline{f}$, which are composed “pointwise”, i.e., for two laws $\underline{f}:\underline{M}\to\underline{N}$, $g:\underline{N}\to\underline{P}$ and all $\Upsilon:\mathbb{A}\to\mathbb{A}^{\prime}\in\mathbf{c}_{\mathbb{K}}$, we have $(\underline{g}\circ\underline{f})_{\mathbb{A}}:=g_{\mathbb{A}}\circ f_{\mathbb% {A}}:M_{\mathbb{A}}\to P_{\mathbb{A}}$, and $(\underline{g}\circ\underline{f})_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}:=g_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime% }}\circ f_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}:M_{\mathbb{A}^{\prime}}\to P_{\mathbb{A}^{% \prime}}$.
