Definition 1.4 (Restricted iteration). A map $f:U\to U^{\prime}$ is called of class $C_{\mathbb{K},n}$ if: it is of class $C_{\mathbb{K}}^{1}$, and, for all $(t_{1},s_{1})\in\mathbb{K}^{2}$, the map $f^{\{1\}}_{(t_{1},s_{1})}$ is of class $C_{\mathbb{K},n-1}$. In this case we define $f^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}:=(f^{\{1\}}_{(t_{1},s_{1})})^{\{2,% \ldots,n\}}_{(t_{2},\ldots,t_{n},s_{2},\ldots,s_{n})}:U^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf% {t},\mathbf{s})}\to(U^{\prime})^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}.$ The map $f^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}$ is defined on the restricted iterated domain $U^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}:=(U^{\{1\}}_{(t_{1},s_{1})})^{\{2,% \ldots,n\}}_{(t_{2},\ldots,t_{n},s_{2},\ldots,s_{n})}.$ We also require that $f^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}$ be jointly continuous both in space and in time variables. In other terms, the inductive definition of $U^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}$ and of $f^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}$ amounts to $\displaystyle U^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}$ $\displaystyle=U^{\{1,\ldots,n\}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}=(\ldots(U_{t_{1},s_% {1}}^{\{1\}})_{(t_{2},s_{2})}^{\{2\}})\ldots)_{(t_{n},s_{n})}^{\{n\}},$ $\displaystyle f^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}$ $\displaystyle=f^{\{1,\ldots,n\}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}:=(\ldots(f_{t_{1},s% _{1}}^{\{1\}})_{(t_{2},s_{2})}^{\{2\}})\ldots)_{(t_{n},s_{n})}^{\{n\}}.$
Definition 2.21. For any subset $N\subset\mathbb{N}$ of finite cardinal $n$, the $2^{n}$-fold direct product algebra of $\mathbb{K}$, in standard order, is the algebra $\mathbb{K}^{2^{n}}:=\mathbb{K}^{{\mathcal{P}}(N)}:=\bigoplus_{A\in{\mathcal{P}% }(N)}\mathbb{K}E_{A}^{N}$ with $\mathbb{K}$-basis $(E_{A}^{N})_{A\in{\mathcal{P}}(N)}$, and product defined on basis elements by $E_{A}\cdot E_{A}=E_{A},\quad\forall A\not=B:E_{A}\cdot E_{B}=0.$ When $N$ is fixed, the notation $E_{A}$ suffices. In particular, this notation is in keeping with our preceding one for the standard basis in $\mathbb{K}^{2}$: $E_{\emptyset}=E_{\emptyset}^{\{1\}}$, $E_{1}=E_{\{1\}}^{\{1\}}$. We simplify notation by writing, e.g., $k$ instead of ${\{k\}}$, and $ij$ instead of ${\{i,j\}}$, etc.
Definition 1.6. For all $(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})\in\mathbb{K}^{2n}$, the $n$-th order anchor of $U\subset V$ is defined as follows: for all locally linear sets $(U,V),(U^{\prime},V^{\prime})$, we consider the map $(U\times U^{\prime})_{(t,s)}\to U_{(t,s)}\times U_{(t,s)}^{\prime},\quad((v_{0% },v_{0}^{\prime}),(v_{1},v_{1}^{\prime}))\mapsto((v_{0},v_{1}),(v_{0}^{\prime}% ,v_{1}^{\prime}))$ as identification. Under such identifications, the map $\Upsilon:=\Upsilon^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}:=$ $(\Upsilon^{\{1\}}_{(t_{1},s_{1})})^{\{2,\ldots,n\}}_{(t_{2},\ldots,t_{n},s_{2}% ,\ldots,s_{n})}:U^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}\to(U^{\{1\}}_{(t_{1},% s_{1})})^{\{2,\ldots,n\}}_{(t_{2},\ldots,t_{n},s_{2},\ldots,s_{n})}\times(U^{% \{1\}}_{(t_{1},s_{1})})^{\{2,\ldots,n\}}_{(t_{2},\ldots,t_{n},s_{2},\ldots,s_{% n})}$ inductively gives rise to a map $\Upsilon^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},\mathbf{s})}:U^{\mathsf{n}}_{(\mathbf{t},% \mathbf{s})}\to U^{2^{n}}$ which we call the $n$-fold anchor.
Definition 2.32. Morphisms of the category of anchored $n$-th order $\mathbb{K}$-tangent algebras are all morphisms of affine type (direct), as well as their compositions with all morphisms coming from the action of the hyperoctahedral group, along with the canonical injection of the trivial anchor morphism, given by the canonical maps $\Phi:\mathbb{K}\to\mathbb{K}_{(t,s)},\,x\mapsto x1$, $\Phi^{\prime}:\mathbb{K}\to\mathbb{K}^{2},\,x\mapsto x1$. In particular, the central inversion belongs to the central element of $\mathfrak{B}_{n}$ (exchanging $a_{i}$ and $b_{i}$ for all $i$, and acting by the complement map on $\mathbb{K}^{{\mathcal{P}}(\mathsf{n})}$).
Definition 2.6. We define the following elements in $\mathbb{K}_{(t,s)}^{\{1\}}$ (the latter if $2\in\mathbb{K}^{\times}$) $\displaystyle a$ $\displaystyle:=e-t1=[X-t],$ $\displaystyle b$ $\displaystyle:=e-s1=[X-s],$ $\displaystyle j$ $\displaystyle:=\frac{a+b}{2}=e-\frac{t+s}{2}.$
Definition 2.1 ( P -flatness) Given a family ${\cal P}$ of indexes, a presheaf $F:A^{op}\rightarrow{\cal V}$ is said ${\cal P}$-flat when its left Kan extension along $Y$, $-*F:[A,{\cal V}]\rightarrow{\cal V}$ preserves all ${\cal P}$-limits. $Flat_{\cal P}$ will denote the family of all ${\cal P}$-flat presheaves, and for any ${\cal V}$-category $A$, $Flat_{\cal P}(A)$ will denote the full subcategory of $[A^{op},{\cal V}]$ with objects ${\cal P}$-flat presheaves.
Definition 2.1. The category $\mathrm{Aut}(P)$ of $P$-automata is defined as follows: • An object of $\mathrm{Aut}(P)$ is a tuple $\displaystyle\mathcal{A}$ $\displaystyle=\langle\,\{{\mathtt{in}}_{i}:Q_{i}\rTo Q\}_{i\in I},\{s_{i}\}_{i% \in I},\{h_{i}\}_{i\in I}\,\rangle$ where: – $\{{\mathtt{in}}_{i}:Q_{i}\rTo Q\}_{i\in I}$ is a coproduct diagram in ${\mathcal{C}}$, – $s_{i}:F_{i}Q_{i}\rTo Q$ for each $i\in I$, – $h_{i}:A_{i}\rTo\Omega_{i}$ for each $i\in I$. • An arrow $f$ from $\mathcal{A}$ to $\mathcal{B}$ is an arrow $f:Q^{\mathcal{A}}\rTo Q^{\mathcal{B}}$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ such that: – ${\mathtt{in}}^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}\cdot f$ factors (uniquely because of Lemma 1.2) through ${\mathtt{in}}^{\mathcal{B}}_{i}$: $\displaystyle{\mathtt{in}}^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}\cdot f$ $\displaystyle=f_{i}\cdot{\mathtt{in}}^{\mathcal{B}}_{i}\,,$ – for each $i\in I$ the following equations hold: $\displaystyle s^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}\cdot f$ $\displaystyle=F_{i}f_{i}\cdot s^{\mathcal{B}}_{i}\,,$ $\displaystyle h^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}$ $\displaystyle=f_{i}\cdot h^{\mathcal{B}}_{i}\,.$
Definition 2.5. For a $P$-automaton $\mathcal{A}$ the $Q$-automaton $K(\mathcal{A})$ is defined as follows. We let $Q^{K(\mathcal{A})}_{0}$ be the terminal object, and $Q^{K(\mathcal{A})}_{i}=Q^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}$ for $i\in I$; the coproduct diagram is given by: $1\rTo^{{\mathtt{in}}_{l}}1+Q^{\mathcal{A}}\lTo^{{\mathtt{in}}_{r}}Q^{\mathcal{% A}}\lTo^{{\mathtt{in}}^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}}Q^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}\,.$ The actions $s_{i,j}$ are defined as follows: $\displaystyle s_{i,j}$ $\displaystyle=\left\{\begin{array}[]{r@{\hspace{0mm}}ll}s^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}% \cdot{\mathtt{in}}_{r}\hskip 0.0pt&:F_{i}Q^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}\rTo Q^{\mathcal{A% }}\rTo 1+Q^{\mathcal{A}}\,,&i=j\,,\\ !\cdot{\mathtt{in}}_{l}\hskip 0.0pt&:F_{i}Q^{\mathcal{A}}_{j}\rTo 1\rTo 1+Q^{% \mathcal{A}}\,,&\textrm{otherwise}.\end{array}\right.$ Finally, the labeling is unchanged: $h^{K(\mathcal{A})}_{i}=h^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}$. Clearly, if $f$ is a morphism in $\mathrm{Aut}(P)$, then $1+f$ is a morphism in $\mathrm{Aut}(Q)$, so that the construction $K$ defines a functor from $\mathrm{Aut}(P)$ to $\mathrm{Aut}(Q)$.
Definition 2.7. We denote by $\delta$-$\mathrm{Aut}(Q)$ the full subcategory category of $\mathrm{Aut}(Q)$ of those $Q$-automata $\mathcal{B}$ for which $s^{\mathcal{B}}_{i,i}$ factors through $Q^{\mathcal{B}}_{I}$ and $s^{\mathcal{B}}_{i,j}$ factors through $Q^{\mathcal{B}}_{0}$ for $i\neq j$.
Definition 2.2. The category $\mathrm{Aut}(Q)$ of $Q$-automata is defined as follows: • An object of $\mathrm{Aut}(Q)$ is a tuple $\displaystyle\mathcal{A}$ $\displaystyle=\langle\,\{{\mathtt{in}}_{j}:Q_{j}\rTo Q\}_{j\in J},\{s_{i,j}\}_% {i\in I,j\in J},\{h_{i}\}_{i\in I}\,\rangle$ where: – $\{{\mathtt{in}}_{j}:Q_{j}\rTo Q\}_{j\in J}$ is a coproduct diagram in ${\mathcal{C}}$, – $s_{i,j}:F_{i}Q_{j}\rTo Q$ for each $i\in I$ and $j\in J$, – $h_{i}:Q_{i}\rTo\Omega_{i}$ for each $i\in I$. • An arrow $f:\mathcal{A}\rTo\mathcal{B}$ is an arrow $f:Q^{\mathcal{A}}\rTo Q^{\mathcal{B}}$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ such that: – for each $j\in J$, ${\mathtt{in}}^{\mathcal{A}}_{j}\cdot f$ factors (necessarily uniquely) through ${\mathtt{in}}^{\mathcal{B}}_{j}$: $\displaystyle{\mathtt{in}}^{\mathcal{A}}_{j}\cdot f$ $\displaystyle=f_{j}\cdot{\mathtt{in}}^{\mathcal{B}}_{j}\,,$ – for each $i\in I$ and $j\in J$ the following equations hold: $\displaystyle s^{\mathcal{A}}_{i,j}\cdot f$ $\displaystyle=F_{i}f_{j}\cdot s^{\mathcal{B}}_{i,j}\,,$ $\displaystyle h^{\mathcal{A}}_{i}$ $\displaystyle=f_{i}\cdot h^{\mathcal{B}}_{i}\,.$
Definition 3.17 Let $(X,\tau)$ be a Tychonoff space. An LCA $(RC(X,\tau),\rho,{\rm I}\!{\rm B})$ is said to be admissible for $(X,\tau)$ if it satisfies the following conditions: (A1) if $F,G\in RC(X)$ and $F\cap G\neq\emptyset$ then $F\rho G$ (i.e. $\rho_{X}\subseteq\rho$ (see [4, 1.10] for $\rho_{X}$)); (A2) if $F\in RC(X)$ and $x\in\mbox{{\rm int}}_{X}(F)$ then there exists $G\in{\rm I}\!{\rm B}$ such that $x\in\mbox{{\rm int}}_{X}(G)$ and $G\ll_{\rho}F$. The set of all LCAs which are admissible for $(X,\tau)$ will be denoted by ${\cal L}_{ad}(X,\tau)$ (or simply by ${\cal L}_{ad}(X)$). If $(RC(X),\rho_{i},{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{i})\in{\cal L}_{ad}(X)$, where $i=1,2$, then we set $(RC(X),\rho_{1},{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{1})\preceq_{l}(RC(X),\rho_{2},{\rm I}\!{\rm B% }_{2})$ iff $\rho_{2}\subseteq\rho_{1}$ and ${\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{2}\subseteq{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{1}$.
Definition 3.7 Let $X$ be a locally compact Hausdorff space and $\Psi^{t}(X)=(A,\rho,{\rm I}\!{\rm B})$. We will denote by ${\cal L}_{a}(X)$ the set of all LCAs of the form $(A,\rho_{1},{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{1})$ which satisfy the following conditions: (LA1) $\rho\subseteq\rho_{1}$; (LA2) ${\rm I}\!{\rm B}\subseteq{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{1}$; (LA3) for every $a\in A$ and every $b\in{\rm I}\!{\rm B}$, $b\rho_{1}a$ implies $b\rho a$. We will define two orders on the set ${\cal L}_{a}(X)$. If $(A,\rho_{i},{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{i})\in{\cal L}_{a}(X)$, where $i=1,2$, we set $(A,\rho_{1},{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{1})\preceq(A,\rho_{2},{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{2})$ (respectively, $(A,\rho_{1},{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{1})\preceq_{s}(A,\rho_{2},{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{2})$) iff $\rho_{2}\subseteq\rho_{1}$ and ${\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{2}\subseteq{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{1}$ (and, respectively, in addition, for every bounded ultrafilter $u$ in $(A,\rho_{1},{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{1})$ there exists $b\in{\rm I}\!{\rm B}_{2}$ such that $b\rho_{1}u$).
Definition 1.9 Let ${\bf DInSkePerLC}$ be the category whose objects are all complete local contact algebras (see [4, 1.14]) and whose morphisms are all ${\bf DSkePerLC}$-morphisms (see [4, 2.14]) which satisfy condition (LS) (see 1.5). Let ${\bf DInSkeC}$ be the category whose objects are all complete normal contact algebras (see [4, 1.1]) and whose morphisms are all ${\bf DSkeC}$-morphisms (see [4, 2.12]) $\varphi:(A,C)\longrightarrow(B,C^{\prime})$ which satisfy the following condition: (FS) $\forall a,b\in B$, $\varphi_{\Lambda}(a)C\varphi_{\Lambda}(b)$ implies $aC^{\prime}b$.
Definition 1.2 Let ${\bf DSuSkeLC}$ be the category whose objects are all complete local contact algebras (see [4, 1.14]) and whose morphisms are all ${\bf DSkeLC}$-morphisms (see [4, 2.10]) $\varphi:(A,\rho,{\rm I}\!{\rm B})\longrightarrow(B,\eta,{\rm I}\!{\rm B}^{% \prime})$ which satisfy the following condition: (IS) For every bounded ultrafilter $u$ in $(A,\rho,{\rm I}\!{\rm B})$ there exists a bounded ultrafilter $v$ in $(B,\eta,{\rm I}\!{\rm B}^{\prime})$ such that $\varphi_{\Lambda}(v)\rho u$ (see [4, 1.18] and [4, 1.21] for the notations). Using [4, Corollary 1.5, (EL1), (36), 1.21], we obtain easily that ${\bf DSuSkeLC}$ is indeed a category.
Definition 2.5 Let $(A,\rho,{\rm I}\!{\rm B})$ be a CLCA. An ideal $I$ of $A$ is called a $\delta$-ideal if $I\subseteq{\rm I}\!{\rm B}$ and for any $a\in I$ there exists $b\in I$ such that $a\ll_{\rho}b$. If $I_{1}$ and $I_{2}$ are two $\delta$-ideals of $(A,\rho,{\rm I}\!{\rm B})$ then we put $I_{1}\leq I_{2}$ iff $I_{1}\subseteq I_{2}$. We will denote by $(I(A,\rho,{\rm I}\!{\rm B}),\leq)$ the poset of all $\delta$-ideals of $(A,\rho,{\rm I}\!{\rm B})$.
Definition 3.22 Let $(X,\tau)$ be a Tychonoff space. An NCA $(RC(X,\tau),C)$ is said to be admissible for $(X,\tau)$ if it satisfies the following conditions: (AK1) if $F,G\in RC(X)$ and $F\cap G\neq\emptyset$ then $FCG$ (i.e. $\rho_{X}\subseteq C$); (AK2) if $F\in RC(X)$ and $x\in\mbox{{\rm int}}_{X}(F)$ then there exists $G\in RC(X)$ such that $x\in\mbox{{\rm int}}_{X}(G)$ and $G\ll_{C}F$. The set of all NCAs which are admissible for $(X,\tau)$ will be denoted by ${\cal K}_{ad}(X,\tau)$ (or simply by ${\cal K}_{ad}(X)$). If $(RC(X),C_{i})\in{\cal K}_{ad}(X)$, where $i=1,2$, then we set $(RC(X),C_{1})\preceq_{ad}(RC(X),C_{2})$ iff $C_{2}\subseteq C_{1}$.
Definition 1.5 Let ${\bf DInSkeLC}$ be the category whose objects are all complete local contact algebras (see [4, 1.14]) and whose morphisms are all ${\bf DSkeLC}$-morphisms (see [4, 2.10]) $\varphi:(A,\rho,{\rm I}\!{\rm B})\longrightarrow(B,\eta,{\rm I}\!{\rm B}^{% \prime})$ which satisfy the following condition: (LS) $\forall a,b\in{\rm I}\!{\rm B}^{\prime}$, $\varphi_{\Lambda}(a)\rho\varphi_{\Lambda}(b)$ implies $a\eta b$ (see [4, 1.21] for $\varphi_{\Lambda}$). It is easy to see that ${\bf DInSkeLC}$ is indeed a category.
Definition 4 Let $G$ and $H$ be small categories. Suppose that $\varphi:H^{(0)}\rightarrow G^{(0)}$. We let $G\times^{\varphi}H\ :=\ \{(g,h)\in G\times H:{\textbf{s}}(g)=\varphi({\textbf{% t}}(h))=\varphi({\textbf{s}}(h))\}.$ A left action of $G$ on $H$ with respect to $\varphi$ is a map $(g,h)\mapsto\alpha_{g}(h)$ from $G\times^{\varphi}H$ to $H$ such that for any $(g^{\prime},g)\in G^{(2)}$, $(h^{\prime},h)\in H^{(2)}$ and $u\in H^{(0)}$ with $(g,h),(g,u),(g,h^{\prime})\in G\times^{\varphi}H$, we have: (0). ${\textbf{s}}(\alpha_{g}(u))={\textbf{t}}(\alpha_{g}(u))$; (I). ${\textbf{s}}(\alpha_{g}({\textbf{s}}(h)))={\textbf{s}}(\alpha_{g}(h))$ ; (II). ${\textbf{t}}(\alpha_{g}({\textbf{t}}(h)))={\textbf{t}}(\alpha_{g}(h))$; (III). $\varphi({\textbf{s}}(\alpha_{g}(u)))={\textbf{t}}(g)$; (IV). $\alpha_{\varphi({\textbf{t}}(h))}(h)=h$; (V). $\alpha_{g^{\prime}}(\alpha_{g}(h))=\alpha_{g^{\prime}g}(h)$; (VI). $\alpha_{g}(h^{\prime}h)=\alpha_{g}(h^{\prime})\alpha_{g}(h)$. For simplicity, we say that $(\varphi,\alpha)$ (or simply $\alpha$ if $\varphi$ is understood) is a left action of $G$ on $H$.
Definition 1 Let $X$ be a set and $R$ be an equivalence relation on $X$. Suppose that $G_{\xi}$ is a group for any $\xi\in X/R$. Then $(X,R,\{G_{\xi}\}_{\xi\in X/R})$ (or simply $\{G_{\xi}\}_{\xi\in X/R}$) is called a group bundle over the equivalence classes of $R$.
Definition 8.1. Let $C$ be a strict monoidal category and let $x\in C$. A half braiding $e_{x}$ for $x$ is a family $\{e_{x}(y)\in\operatorname{Hom}_{C}(xy,yx),y\in C\}$ of isomorphisms satisfying (i) Naturality: $f\otimes id_{x}\circ e_{x}(y)=e_{x}(z)\circ id_{x}\otimes f\>\>\>\forall f:y% \rightarrow z.$ (ii) The braid relation: $e_{x}(y\otimes z)=id_{y}\otimes e_{x}(z)\circ e_{x}(y)\otimes id_{z}\>\>\>% \forall y,z\in C$. (iii) Unit property: $e_{x}(1)=id_{x}$.
Definition 7.1. Let $d_{i}$ be the quantum dimensions of all simple types $X_{i},i=1,\cdots,n$ of an MTC $\mathcal{C}$, $\theta_{i}$ be the twists, define the total quantum order of $\mathcal{C}$ to be $D=\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{n}d_{i}^{2}}$, and $D_{+}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\theta_{i}d_{i}^{2}$. Then $\frac{D_{+}}{D}=e^{\frac{\pi ic}{4}}$ for some rational number $c$. The rational number $c$ defined modulo $8$ will be called the topological central charge of the MTC $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 8.3. The quantum double $\mathcal{Z}(C)$ of a strict monoidal category $C$ has as objects pairs $(x,e_{x})$, where $x\in C$ and $e_{x}$ is a half braiding. The morphisms are given by $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{Z}(C)}((x,e_{x}),(y,e_{y}))=\{f\in\operatorname{% Hom}_{C}(x,y)|id_{z}\otimes f\circ e_{x}(z)=e_{y}(z)\circ f\otimes id_{z}\>\>% \>\forall z\in C\}$. The tensor product of objects is given by $(x,e_{x})\otimes(y,e_{y})=(xy,e_{xy})$, where $e_{xy}(z)=e_{x}(z)\otimes id_{y}\circ id_{x}\otimes e_{y}(z)$. The tensor unit is $(1,e_{1})$ where $e_{1}(x)=id_{x}$. The composition and tensor product of morphisms are inherited from $C$. The braiding is given by $c((x,e_{x}),(y,e_{y}))=e_{x}(y)$.
Definition 2.2. A model category ${\operatorname{\mathbf{M}}}$ is left proper if for each pushout square in ${\operatorname{\mathbf{M}}}$ of the form $\xymatrix{{A}\ar[r]^{i}\ar[d]_{f}&{B}\ar[d]^{g}\\ {C}\ar[r]&{D}}$ in which $i$ is a cofibration and $f$ is weak equivalence, the map $g$ is weak equivalence. Similarly, ${\operatorname{\mathbf{M}}}$ is right proper if it satisfies the dual property involving pullback squares, fibrations, and weak equivalences. A model category ${\operatorname{\mathbf{M}}}$ is proper if it is both left proper and right proper.
Definition. Let $S$ be a set. An ultrafilter on $S$ is a subset $\mathcal{U}$ of $2^{S}$, the power set of $S$, such that: (1) $\emptyset\not\in\mathcal{U}$, (2) $A\in\mathcal{U},A\subset B\implies B\in\mathcal{U}$, (3) $A\in\mathcal{U},B\in\mathcal{U}\implies A\cap B\in\mathcal{U}$, (4) $A\not\in\mathcal{U}\implies S\setminus A\in\mathcal{U}$.
Definition. The inverse limit of an inverse family $(X_{i},f_{ij})$ in a category $\mathcal{C}$ is the universal object $X$ (unique up to a unique isomorphism) equipped with arrows $\pi_{i}:X\to X_{i}$ with $\pi_{j}=f_{ij}\circ\pi_{i}$. That is, $X$ is such that for any $Y\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathcal{C})$ and collection of maps $u_{i}:Y\to X_{i}$ such that $u_{j}=f_{ij}\circ u_{i}$ for all $f_{ij}$, there exists a unique $u:Y\to X$ such that the diagram $\xymatrix@=50pt{&Y\ar@{-->}[d]^{u}\ar[ddl]_{u_{i}}\ar[ddr]^{u_{j}}&\\ &X\ar[dl]^{\pi_{i}}\ar[dr]_{\pi_{j}}&\\ X_{i}\ar[rr]^{f_{ij}}&&X_{j}}$ commutes for all $f_{ij}$.
B.1 Definition. Let $K$ be a non-empty connected simplicial set. Let $X$ be an object of ${\rm{\mathbf{MdTop}}}_{\Delta}$. Let $X\otimes K=|K|\boxtimes X$ where $|K|$ means the geometric realization of $K$ [GJ99].
5.1 Definition. (Compare with [Gau03, Definition 7.2 and Proposition 7.5]) Let $f,g:X\rightrightarrows Y$ be two morphisms of multipointed $d$-spaces. Then $f$ and $g$ are S-homotopic if there exists a continuous map $H:[0,1]\rightarrow{\rm{\mathbf{MDTOP}}}_{\Delta}(X,Y)$ called a S-homotopy such that $H(0)=f$ and $H(1)=g$. This situation is denoted by $\sim_{S}$. Two multipointed $d$-spaces $X$ and $Y$ are S-homotopy equivalent if and only if there exist two morphisms $f:X\leftrightarrows Y:g$ with $g\circ f\sim_{S}\operatorname{Id}_{X}$ and $f\circ g\sim_{S}\operatorname{Id}_{Y}$.
5.7 Definition. A continuous map $i:A\rightarrow B$ of general topological spaces is an inclusion of a strong deformation retract of spaces if there exists a continuous map $H:[0,1]\times B\rightarrow B$ called the deformation retract such that • $H(0,-)=\operatorname{Id}_{B}$, $H(1,-)=i\circ r$ where $r:B\rightarrow A$ is a map of multipointed $d$-spaces such that $r\circ i=\operatorname{Id}_{A}$ • $H(t,i(a))=i(a)$ for all $a\in A$ and for all $t\in[0,1]$.
3.1 Definition. A multipointed space is a pair $(|X|,X^{0})$ where • $|X|$ is a $\Delta$-generated space called the underlying space of $X$. • $X^{0}$ is a subset of $|X|$ called the $0$-skeleton of $X$. A morphism of multipointed spaces $f:X=(|X|,X^{0})\rightarrow Y=(|Y|,Y^{0})$ is a commutative square $\xymatrix{X^{0}\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{f^{0}}\ar@{->}[d]_{-}{}&Y^{0}\ar@{->}[d]_{-}{}% \\ |X|\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{|f|}&|Y|.}$ The corresponding category is denoted by ${\rm{\mathbf{MTop}}}_{\Delta}$.
5.3 Definition. Let $X$ be a multipointed $d$-space. The multipointed $d$-space $[0,1]\boxtimes X$ is called the cylinder of $X$.
7.1 Definition. [Gau03] A flow $X$ is a small category without identity maps enriched over topological spaces. The composition law of a flow is denoted by $*$. The set of objects is denoted by $X^{0}$. The space of morphisms from $\alpha$ to $\beta$ is denoted by $\mathbb{P}_{\alpha,\beta}X$. Let $\mathbb{P}X$ be the disjoint sum of the spaces $\mathbb{P}_{\alpha,\beta}X$. A morphism of flows $f:X\rightarrow Y$ is a set map $f^{0}:X^{0}\rightarrow Y^{0}$ together with a continuous map $\mathbb{P}f:\mathbb{P}X\rightarrow\mathbb{P}Y$ preserving the structure. The corresponding category is denoted by ${\rm{\mathbf{Flow}}}({\mathbf{Top}}_{\Delta})$, ${\rm{\mathbf{Flow}}}({\mathbf{Top}}_{\mathcal{K}})$, etc… depending on the category of topological spaces we are considering.
4.1 Definition. A globular complex is a multipointed $d$-space $X$ such that the map $X^{0}\rightarrow X$ is a relative $I^{gl,top}$-cell complex. The set of cells of $X^{0}\rightarrow X$ is called the globular decomposition of the globular complex.
B.2 Definition. Let $K$ be a non-empty simplicial set. Let $(K_{i})_{i\in I}$ be its set of non-empty connected components. Let $X\otimes K:=\bigsqcup_{i\in I}X\otimes K_{i}$. And let $X\otimes\varnothing=\varnothing$.
5.2 Definition. (Compare with [Gau03, Proposition 8.1]) Let $X$ be a multipointed $d$-space. Let $U$ be a non-empty connected $\Delta$-generated space. Then the multipointed $d$-space $U\boxtimes X$ is defined as follows: • Let $(U\boxtimes X)^{0}=X^{0}$. • Let $|U\boxtimes X|$ be defined by the pushout diagram of spaces $\xymatrix{U\times_{\Delta}X^{0}\ar@{->}[d]_{-}{}\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{}&U\times_{% \Delta}|X|\ar@{->}[d]_{-}{}\\ X^{0}\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{}&\ar@{-}[]+L+<-6pt,+2pt>;[]+LU+<-6pt,+6pt>\ar@{-}[]+U+<-% 2pt,+6pt>;[]+LU+<-6pt,+6pt>{|U\boxtimes X|}.}$ • The set $\mathbb{P}_{\alpha,\beta}^{top}(U\boxtimes X)$ is the smallest subset of continuous maps from $[0,1]$ to $|U\boxtimes X|$ containing the continuous maps $\phi:[0,1]\rightarrow|U\boxtimes X|$ of the form $t\mapsto(u,\phi_{2}(t))$ where $u\in[0,1]$ and $\phi_{2}\in\mathbb{P}_{\alpha,\beta}^{top}X$ and closed under composition $*_{1/2}$ and strictly increasing reparametrization.
3.3 Definition. A multipointed $d$-space $X$ is a triple $(|X|,X^{0},\mathbb{P}^{top}X)$ where • $(|X|,X^{0})$ is a multipointed space. • The set $\mathbb{P}^{top}X$ is the disjoint union of the sets $\mathbb{P}_{\alpha,\beta}^{top}X$ for $(\alpha,\beta)$ running over $X^{0}\times X^{0}$ where $\mathbb{P}_{\alpha,\beta}^{top}X$ is a set of continuous paths $\phi$ from $[0,1]$ to $|X|$ such that $\phi(0)=\alpha$ and $\phi(1)=\beta$ which is closed under composition $*_{1/2}$ and under strictly increasing reparametrization 2These two facts imply that the set of paths is closed under $*_{t}$ for any $t\in]0,1[$., that is for every $\phi\in\mathbb{P}^{top}_{\alpha,\beta}X$ and for any strictly increasing continuous map $\psi:[0,1]\rightarrow[0,1]$ with $\psi(0)=0$ and $\psi(1)=1$, $\phi\circ\psi\in\mathbb{P}^{top}_{\alpha,\beta}X$. The element of $\mathbb{P}^{top}X$ are called execution path or $d$-path. A morphism of multipointed $d$-spaces $f:X=(|X|,X^{0},\mathbb{P}^{top}X)\rightarrow Y=(|Y|,Y^{0},\mathbb{P}^{top}Y)$ is a commutative square $\xymatrix{X^{0}\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{f^{0}}\ar@{->}[d]_{-}{}&Y^{0}\ar@{->}[d]_{-}{}% \\ |X|\ar@{->}[r]^{-}{|f|}&|Y|}$ such that for every $\phi\in\mathbb{P}^{top}X$, one has $|f|\circ\phi\in\mathbb{P}^{top}Y$. Let $\mathbb{P}^{top}f(\phi)=|f|\circ\phi$. The corresponding category is denoted by ${\rm{\mathbf{MdTop}}}_{\Delta}$.
6.1 Definition. (Compare with [Gau03, Definition 11.6]) A morphism $f:X\rightarrow Y$ of multipointed $d$-spaces is a weak S-homotopy equivalence if $f^{0}:X^{0}\rightarrow Y^{0}$ is a bijection of sets and if $\mathbb{P}^{top}f:\mathbb{P}^{top}_{\alpha,\beta}X\rightarrow\mathbb{P}^{top}_% {f^{0}(\alpha),f^{0}(\beta)}Y$ is a weak homotopy equivalence of topological spaces. The class of weak S-homotopy equivalences of multipointed $d$-spaces is denoted by $\mathcal{W}^{top}$.
2.10 Definition. A general topological space $X$ is weak Hausdorff if for any continuous map $g:K\rightarrow X$ with $K$ compact, $g(K)$ is closed in $X$. A compactly generated space is a weak Hausdorff $k$-space.
5.6 Definition. A map $i:A\rightarrow B$ of multipointed $d$-spaces is an inclusion of a strong deformation retract if there exists a continuous map $H:[0,1]\rightarrow{\rm{\mathbf{MDTOP}}}_{\Delta}(B,B)$ called the deformation retract such that • $H(0)=\operatorname{Id}_{B}$, $H(1)=i\circ r$ where $r:B\rightarrow A$ is a map of multipointed $d$-spaces such that $r\circ i=\operatorname{Id}_{A}$ • $|\widetilde{H}|(t,i(a))=i(a)$ for all $a\in A$ and for all $t\in[0,1]$.
A.3 Definition. [DI04, p 686] An inclusion of spaces $f:Y\rightarrow Z$ is a relative $T_{1}$-inclusion of spaces if for any open set $U$ of $Y$ and any point $z\in Z\backslash U$, there is an open set $W$ of $Z$ with $U\subset W$ and $z\notin W$.
2.4 Definition. (e.g., [Bor94b, Proposition 7.1.5] or [Lew78, p 160]) Let $X$ and $Y$ be two general topological spaces. The space $\mathcal{T}_{t}(X,Y)$ is the set of continuous maps $\mathcal{T}(X,Y)$ from $X$ to $Y$ equipped with the topology generated by the subbasis $N(h,U)$ where $h:K\rightarrow X$ is a continuous map from a compact $K$ to $X$, where $U$ is an open of $Y$ and where $N(h,U)=\{f:X\rightarrow Y,f(h(K))\subset U\}$. This topology is called the compact-open topology.
Definition 3.1 Suppose that $A$ is a $C^{*}$-algebra and $G$ is a discrete groupoid. A quasi action of $G$ on $A$ is a map $\beta$ from $G$ to $\mathcal{N}(A)\triangleq\{(\varphi,\mathcal{D}(\varphi))\ |\ \varphi:\ A% \rightarrow A\ {\rm is\ a\ *-homomorphism};\ \mathcal{D}(\varphi)\subseteq A\ % {\rm is\ a\ closed\ *-subalgebra};\ \varphi|_{\mathcal{D}(\varphi)}:\mathcal{D% }(\varphi)\rightarrow\varphi(A)\ {\rm is\ a\ *-isomorphism}\}$, satisfying (I). if $(s,t)\in G^{(2)}$, then $\beta_{t}(A)=\mathcal{D}(\beta_{s})$, $\mathcal{D}(\beta_{st})=\mathcal{D}(\beta_{t})$, and $\beta_{st}=\beta_{s}\beta_{t}$. (II). if $(s,t)\notin G^{(2)}$, then $\beta_{s}\beta_{t}=0$. Also we call $(A,G,\beta)$ a $quasi\ C^{*}-dynamical\ system$.
